## 3. Component Implementations

### 3a. `Stepper` (root container, `data-slot="stepper"`)

```typescript
"use client"

function Stepper({
  className,
  orientation = "horizontal",
  activeStep: activeStepProp,
  defaultStep = 1,
  onStepChange,
  totalSteps = 0,
  ...props
}: StepperProps) {
  const [_activeStep, _setActiveStep] = React.useState(defaultStep)
  const activeStep = activeStepProp ?? _activeStep

  const handleStepChange = React.useCallback(
    (step: number) => {
      if (onStepChange) {
        onStepChange(step)
      } else {
        _setActiveStep(step)
      }
    },
    [onStepChange]
  )

  return (
    <StepperContext.Provider
      value={{ orientation, activeStep, totalSteps, onStepChange: handleStepChange }}
    >
      <div
        data-slot="stepper"
        data-orientation={orientation}
        className={cn(
          "group/stepper flex",
          "data-[orientation=horizontal]:flex-row data-[orientation=horizontal]:items-start",
          "data-[orientation=vertical]:flex-col data-[orientation=vertical]:items-start",
          className
        )}
        {...props}
      />
    </StepperContext.Provider>
  )
}
```

Key points:
- `data-orientation` enables CSS selectors on children via `group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:` and `group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:`.
- The `group/stepper` class establishes the named group scope for all descendants.
- No `"use client"` needed on the file — the root component uses state so the whole file should have `"use client"` at the top, matching `carousel.tsx`, `sidebar.tsx`, and `toggle-group.tsx`.

### 3b. `StepperItem` (`data-slot="stepper-item"`)

```typescript
function StepperItem({
  className,
  step,
  disabled = false,
  ...props
}: StepperItemProps) {
  const { activeStep } = useStepper()

  const state: StepState =
    step === activeStep ? "active"
    : step < activeStep ? "completed"
    : "inactive"

  return (
    <StepperItemContext.Provider value={{ step, state, disabled }}>
      <div
        data-slot="stepper-item"
        data-state={state}
        data-disabled={disabled ? "" : undefined}
        className={cn(
          "group/stepper-item flex",
          // Horizontal: each item is a column (indicator + content stacked), items flow in a row
          "group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:flex-col group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:items-center",
          // Vertical: each item is a row (indicator left, content right)
          "group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:flex-row group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:items-start group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:gap-4",
          "data-[disabled]:pointer-events-none data-[disabled]:opacity-50",
          className
        )}
        {...props}
      />
    </StepperItemContext.Provider>
  )
}
```

Key points:
- `data-state` carries `"active" | "completed" | "inactive"` — child components use `data-[state=active]:` and `data-[state=completed]:` selectors to self-style.
- `data-disabled=""` (empty-string attribute presence) is checked with `data-[disabled]:` in Tailwind. Using `undefined` when false means the attribute is absent, so the selector won't match.
- `group/stepper-item` class scopes child selectors.

### 3c. `StepperTrigger` (`data-slot="stepper-trigger"`)

This is the most visually complex piece. It wraps a `<button>` and renders the step indicator circle.

```typescript
function StepperTrigger({
  className,
  children,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentProps<"button">) {
  const { onStepChange } = useStepper()
  const { step, state, disabled } = useStepperItem()

  return (
    <button
      data-slot="stepper-trigger"
      data-state={state}
      type="button"
      disabled={disabled}
      onClick={() => onStepChange?.(step)}
      className={cn(
        // Layout: trigger contains the circle indicator + optional label slot
        "group/stepper-trigger inline-flex flex-col items-center gap-2",
        "text-sm font-medium outline-none",
        "disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50",
        "focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-[3px] focus-visible:ring-ring/50",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    >
      {/* Step indicator circle */}
      <span
        className={cn(
          "flex size-8 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border-2 transition-all",
          // Inactive state
          "border-border bg-muted text-muted-foreground",
          // Active state
          "data-[state=active]:border-primary data-[state=active]:bg-primary data-[state=active]:text-primary-foreground",
          // Completed state
          "data-[state=completed]:border-primary data-[state=completed]:bg-primary data-[state=completed]:text-primary-foreground",
        )}
        data-state={state}
      >
        {state === "completed" ? (
          <CheckIcon className="size-4" aria-hidden="true" />
        ) : (
          <span className="text-xs font-semibold">{step}</span>
        )}
      </span>
      {children}
    </button>
  )
}
```

Notes on the indicator circle:
- `size-8` (32px) is consistent with `size-9` used in `BreadcrumbEllipsis` and `PaginationEllipsis`. `size-8` is slightly more compact and better for inline step indicators.
- `border-2` provides a visible ring without needing a separate outline element.
- The `data-state` attribute is duplicated on the inner `<span>` so Tailwind data selectors work independently on that element (the button itself carries it too for external CSS targeting).
- `CheckIcon` comes from `lucide-react`, consistent with `checkbox.tsx`, `context-menu.tsx`, `menubar.tsx`, `dropdown-menu.tsx`.
- The `children` prop of `StepperTrigger` renders after the circle — this lets users optionally put a label inline. Typically the label goes in `StepperTitle` outside the trigger, but the trigger needs to be composable.

Regarding `onStepChange` call: this pulls the function from the root stepper context. Since `onStepChange` is the internal handler (not the user's callback), it handles both controlled and uncontrolled state internally.

### 3d. `StepperTitle` (`data-slot="stepper-title"`)

```typescript
function StepperTitle({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"p">) {
  const { state } = useStepperItem()
  return (
    <p
      data-slot="stepper-title"
      data-state={state}
      className={cn(
        "text-sm font-medium leading-none",
        "text-muted-foreground",
        "data-[state=active]:text-foreground",
        "data-[state=completed]:text-foreground",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}
```

### 3e. `StepperDescription` (`data-slot="stepper-description"`)

```typescript
function StepperDescription({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"p">) {
  return (
    <p
      data-slot="stepper-description"
      className={cn("text-xs text-muted-foreground", className)}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}
```

`StepperDescription` doesn't need state-based styling — it always stays muted. This is consistent with `CardDescription`.

### 3f. `StepperSeparator` (`data-slot="stepper-separator"`)

```typescript
function StepperSeparator({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"div">) {
  const { orientation } = useStepper()
  const { state } = useStepperItem()

  // "completed" means the step this separator follows is already done
  const isCompleted = state === "completed"

  return (
    <div
      data-slot="stepper-separator"
      data-orientation={orientation}
      aria-hidden="true"
      className={cn(
        "shrink-0 bg-border transition-colors",
        // Completed: fill with primary color
        isCompleted && "bg-primary",
        // Horizontal orientation: thin horizontal line
        "group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:h-px group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:w-full group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:flex-1 group-data-[orientation=horizontal]/stepper:min-w-8",
        // Vertical orientation: thin vertical line
        "group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:w-px group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:h-full group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:min-h-8 group-data-[orientation=vertical]/stepper:self-stretch",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}
```

Key design decision on separator placement: the separator sits between `StepperItem` elements. The developer places `<StepperSeparator />` as a direct child of `<Stepper>` between each pair of `<StepperItem>` nodes. This is the same approach as `<BreadcrumbSeparator />` in the breadcrumb component. Since the separator sits *outside* a `StepperItem`, it cannot directly read `StepperItemContext`. Two solutions:

**Option A** — Separator is placed *inside* `StepperItem` at the end: `StepperItem` wraps both its content and a trailing separator. This couples them.

**Option B** — Separator is placed *between* `StepperItem` nodes as a sibling and reads the *preceding* item's context via a wrapper. This requires a different context approach.

**Recommended approach (Option C)**: The separator is placed inside the `StepperItem` as its last child. The `step` prop on `StepperItem` tells the root context whether that item is completed. The separator reads `StepperItemContext` of its parent item. Developer usage becomes:

```tsx
<StepperItem step={1}>
  <StepperTrigger />
  <StepperTitle>Step 1</StepperTitle>
  <StepperSeparator />  {/* last separator inside step 1 */}
</StepperItem>
<StepperItem step={2}>
  ...
</StepperItem>
```

This is the cleanest — `StepperSeparator` can always read `useStepperItem()` to know if its enclosing step is completed, and therefore color itself accordingly. The last `StepperItem` simply doesn't include a `StepperSeparator`. This is precisely how the component tree works for both orientations.

For horizontal layout: the separator needs to grow horizontally to fill space between steps. The `Stepper` root uses `flex-row` and the separator uses `flex-1` to expand. Each `StepperItem` is `shrink-0`.

For vertical layout: the separator hangs below the trigger/title area and has a fixed or self-stretch height.

### 3g. `StepperContent` (`data-slot="stepper-content"`)

```typescript
function StepperContent({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"div">) {
  const { state } = useStepperItem()

  // Always in DOM but hidden via CSS when not active (avoids unmount/remount)
  return (
    <div
      data-slot="stepper-content"
      data-state={state}
      hidden={state !== "active"}
      className={cn(
        "data-[state=active]:block hidden",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}
```

Use the `hidden` HTML attribute (not `display:none` via class) for accessibility — when `hidden` is set, the content is fully removed from the accessibility tree. The `data-[state=active]:block` class overrides it for the active step. This is simpler and more accessible than `visibility: hidden` or opacity-based approaches.

