## 5. Component Composition Pattern (How They Nest)

### Horizontal layout

```
<Stepper orientation="horizontal">                  // flex-row, group/stepper
  <StepperItem step={1}>                            // flex-col items-center flex-1
    <StepperTrigger />                              // button with circle indicator
    <StepperTitle>Account</StepperTitle>
    <StepperDescription>...</StepperDescription>
    <StepperSeparator />                            // h-px flex-1, grows to fill gap
  </StepperItem>
  <StepperItem step={2}>
    <StepperTrigger />
    <StepperTitle>Profile</StepperTitle>
    <StepperDescription>...</StepperDescription>
    <StepperSeparator />
  </StepperItem>
  <StepperItem step={3}>
    <StepperTrigger />
    <StepperTitle>Review</StepperTitle>
    <StepperDescription>...</StepperDescription>
    {/* No separator on last item */}
  </StepperItem>
</Stepper>
```

The separator in horizontal mode needs to sit in the row between steps. Because `StepperItem` is `flex-col`, the separator placed as the last child renders below the title — this is wrong for horizontal. A better placement model is:

The separator lives outside the `StepperItem` as a **direct child of `Stepper`**, not inside `StepperItem`. To read whether the preceding step is completed, the separator reads from the root `StepperContext` with a `step` prop of its own:

```typescript
type StepperSeparatorProps = React.ComponentProps<"div"> & {
  afterStep: number   // which step this separator follows
}

function StepperSeparator({ afterStep, className, ...props }: StepperSeparatorProps) {
  const { activeStep } = useStepper()
  const isCompleted = afterStep < activeStep
  ...
}
```

This is cleaner and removes the dependency on `StepperItemContext` entirely. Developer usage:

```tsx
<Stepper orientation="horizontal">
  <StepperItem step={1}>...</StepperItem>
  <StepperSeparator afterStep={1} />
  <StepperItem step={2}>...</StepperItem>
  <StepperSeparator afterStep={2} />
  <StepperItem step={3}>...</StepperItem>
</Stepper>
```

This mirrors the `<BreadcrumbSeparator />` pattern precisely. In horizontal mode, separators are `flex-1` slivers that fill the remaining row space.

### Vertical layout

```
<Stepper orientation="vertical">
  <StepperItem step={1}>
    <StepperTrigger />
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-1 pl-2">
      <StepperTitle>Step 1</StepperTitle>
      <StepperDescription>...</StepperDescription>
      <StepperContent>...body content...</StepperContent>
    </div>
  </StepperItem>
  <StepperSeparator afterStep={1} />
  <StepperItem step={2}>...</StepperItem>
  <StepperSeparator afterStep={2} />
  <StepperItem step={3}>...</StepperItem>
</Stepper>
```

In vertical mode the separator is a vertical line connecting items from top to bottom.

### `StepperContent` placement

`StepperContent` sits inside `StepperItem` alongside the title/description group. In horizontal mode it is typically not used (too cramped). In vertical mode it renders the step's form or body content below the title.

