# Stepper Compound Component — Implementation Plan

## 1. TypeScript Interfaces and Context Types

### Root context (shared across all sub-components)

```typescript
type StepperOrientation = "horizontal" | "vertical"
type StepState = "active" | "completed" | "inactive"

type StepperContextValue = {
  orientation: StepperOrientation
  activeStep: number
  totalSteps: number
  onStepChange?: (step: number) => void
}

const StepperContext = React.createContext<StepperContextValue>({
  orientation: "horizontal",
  activeStep: 1,
  totalSteps: 0,
})
```

### Item context (shared between StepperTrigger, StepperTitle, StepperDescription, StepperContent inside a single item)

```typescript
type StepperItemContextValue = {
  step: number
  state: StepState
  disabled: boolean
}

const StepperItemContext = React.createContext<StepperItemContextValue>({
  step: 1,
  state: "inactive",
  disabled: false,
})
```

### Custom hook for safe context consumption

Both contexts should expose named hooks that throw if called outside the correct ancestor, following the `useSidebar` / `useCarousel` pattern in this codebase:

```typescript
function useStepper(): StepperContextValue {
  const context = React.useContext(StepperContext)
  if (!context) throw new Error("useStepper must be used within a <Stepper />")
  return context
}

function useStepperItem(): StepperItemContextValue {
  const context = React.useContext(StepperItemContext)
  if (!context) throw new Error("useStepperItem must be used within a <StepperItem />")
  return context
}
```

Note: the default context values above make the null-check always true — the real guard is using `React.createContext<StepperContextValue | null>(null)` and checking for null, exactly as `CarouselContext` and `SidebarContext` do in this codebase.

### Component prop types

```typescript
// Stepper (root)
type StepperProps = React.ComponentProps<"div"> & {
  orientation?: StepperOrientation
  activeStep?: number           // controlled
  defaultStep?: number          // uncontrolled
  onStepChange?: (step: number) => void
  totalSteps?: number           // optional override; normally inferred from child count
}

// StepperItem
type StepperItemProps = React.ComponentProps<"div"> & {
  step: number         // 1-indexed
  disabled?: boolean
}

// StepperTrigger
// Extends <button> — no extra props needed beyond what the button already carries.
// className and children are passthrough.

// StepperTitle
// React.ComponentProps<"p"> only

// StepperDescription
// React.ComponentProps<"p"> only

// StepperSeparator
// React.ComponentProps<"div"> only — orientation and completed state are read from context.

// StepperContent
// React.ComponentProps<"div"> only — active state read from StepperItemContext.
```

